<title type="html"><![CDATA[Composing NES music on Mac]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87560#p87560"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Celius wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />when you're done making all your songs they get compiled all into an NSF (NES Sound File). This is what you include in your project if you choose to go with using one of these tools.<br /></div><br />That's wrong. You don't use actual NSF files in games. You can, but this does not make much sense, because you'll have no control on the memory layout and no sound effects support.<br /><br />Instead, you use data generated by the trackers and converters with sound engines that were specifically designed for the purpose of being used in games. They are already there, so you don't have to create your own.<br /><br />Actually, if one so badly want to create his own sound engine, nothing stops him from using trackers or other sound editors to enter music data in a comfortable way. You only need to make rather simple converter that will convert a file with music data into data in the format required by your engine. There is absolutely no need to enter all the music data as hex values in an assembly source, it is major waste of time.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4205">Shiru</a> — Thu Dec 15, 2011 2:59 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
