I'm personally doubt that making a custom sound engine is a good idea. It only make sense when making a custom sound engine is your goal by itself, or when existing engines are not capable for something specific. If you don't need anything special, you would spend major amount of time on this instead of working on actual project, without gaining anything useful in return. Don't forget, it is not only the engine itself, but also some tools for making or converting music and sound effects. If you going to enter music and sound data by hand as hex, it is again time that could be spent on more useful things.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4205">Shiru</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 3:41 pm</p><hr />
