I actually use Cubase 6 as well, but I don't have a way to make stuff in Cubase and have it automatically turned into a sound engine-friendly format for the NES. I just use it for actually composing the music, then I usually enter the data my sound engine would need to play the same thing by hand. It also depends on your sound engine, and what its capabilities are. I would recommend doing your own sound engine rather than using something like Famitracker or NT2. You can save more RAM and tailor their capabilities to your needs.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=138">Celius</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 2:42 pm</p><hr />
