<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Shiru]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-12-13T09:41:15-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-12-13T09:41:15-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87451#p87451</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87451#p87451"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Composing NES music on Mac]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87451#p87451"><![CDATA[
It could give very good result, but it is not program that does it, it depends on your own tracking skills. In theory it is possible to have sound quality on NES that is not achievable with FamiTracker (higher update rates, PCM drums, Neil Baldwin-style auto echo), but it is not often seen or required for actual games.<br /><br />Currently there are two ways to use music created in FamiTracker.<br /><br />First - use the player that is provided by the FamiTracker author, jsr. This way whatever you create with FamiTracker will be playable on NES. There are drawbacks: size of the music data and player code, amount of CPU time used by the player, and lack of sound effects support. It is relatively easy to add sound effects, but not much to do with other drawbacks. Thus the player mostly used for music demos.<br /><br />Second - use FamiTone, a separate sound library that play music that is created with FamiTracker with certain limitations. It has a bit faster and smaller player and a bit more compact data, sound effects are available too. Drawback is that it does not support most of advanced FamiTracker features, so you can't play whatever you created, only music that was specifically composed for the player. The limitations are though, but you can hear in all my NES games that they aren't too bad, you still can have good sound quality.<br /><br /><br />For <a href="http://kkfos.aspekt.fi/projects/nes/tools/pornotracker/" class="postlink">Pornotracker</a> there is the <a href="http://kkfos.aspekt.fi/projects/nes/muse/" class="postlink">MUSE</a> library, feature-wise it is probably something inbetween FamiTracker original player and FamiTone. It has sound effects support as well.<br /><br /><br />There is also a license question that you may want to take into account. FamiTracker itself is GPL, but no license specified for the player, so you may want to ask jsr about it whether it is under GPL too. FamiTone is Public Domain. No license specified for MUSE too, so you may want to ask thefox about it.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4205">Shiru</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 9:41 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
