<author><name><![CDATA[Shiru]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-12-13T04:15:57-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-12-13T04:15:57-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87437#p87437</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87437#p87437"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Composing NES music on Mac]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8405&amp;p=87437#p87437"><![CDATA[
FamiTracker and Pornotracker are both legitimate and actually the easiest ways to make music for NES programs. Not rely on the MIDI import feature too much, though, because amount of the tweaks it'll require is comparable with remaking your MIDI files by the hand (this certainly will work better than import).<br /><br />In any case, waveforms are predefined (pulse with 12.5%, 25% and 50% duty cycle, triangle, noise). The instrument editor only allow to create some volume and pitch envelopes. Trackers in general are a kind of step sequencer.<br /><br />Certainly, a Windows PC is a better platform for NES development, solely because of the fact that most tools are available for Windows only. Luckily, many of them work under Wine well, so you still can use Mac or Linux, it is just not going to be very comfortable.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4205">Shiru</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 4:15 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
